text.tspan: This is the pathbar in it's normal state. You can see that the path "~/Downloads" has been represented as a
breadcrumb with a symbolic home icon and the folder label.
This is the pathbar in it's editable state. You can see the same path has been represented but in an entry
form instead of a button form. This can be triggered by clicking on a separator in the breadcrumb, using
the keyboard shortcut CRTL + L, or simply by typing. The default action for this mode is search.
This is probably the most common usage for the pathbar: a filter with autocompletion. This moves the
awkwardly placed filter from the bottom corner of Nautilus into a location that makes sense. You can see
that the icon has changed to an arrow to communicate that Marlin recognizes "~/Music" as a valid path.
Of course, you can manually type in a path and Marlin will recognize this as well. Any "/" character that
occurs before your entered text will automatically be converted to a ">" graphic. This is to maintain
consistent spacing when the pathbar moves from breadcrumb to edit mode. You will not see the text shift.
